  "opinion": "As a woman in her sixties who's spent most of her life in Washington DC and now works as a waitress, I've always valued the quiet moments of reflection that come from reading novels and watching birds in the garden. Social media, though, has become a double-edged sword. I check it a few times a month, mostly to stay connected with family and friends, but I've noticed an increase in fake news and misleading posts that can be deeply unsettling. My curiosity, which has always led me to explore new things, sometimes makes me click on links that turn out to be harmful or false. I've learned that the best way to manage this is to be more selective about what I share and see. When I see something that seems too good to be true or that conflicts with what I know to be true from my upbringing and faith, I pause and think carefully. I've also started using tools to verify information before sharing it, which is something I learned from my parents, who were both educated to a high level. It's important to remember that as a community member in DC, where we value honesty and respect, spreading false information can harm others. I try to focus on the positive aspects of social media, like sharing stories that uplift and encourage, rather than engaging with the negative. My faith teaches me to be discerning, and I believe that taking a step back to verify information is a sign of wisdom and care for others.",
